ST. LOUIS, MO. 
Dec. 28, '28.
Dear Mamma:
The little jar came through in good shape, and it was more than welcome: Many thanks. Don't send any more, as much as I'd like to have it. If discovered it would make trouble. Just the same, I'm glad you did it once:
I sent the manuscript of STRAWS IN THE WIND to Macmillans yesterday, and I think it will appear in the spring. It is surely worth publishing. I was surprised at the stuff in it. I think you'll enjoy reading it. 
It's the best of news that you are reasonably happy and contented. Lots of women wouldn't be, and you should hear <del>here</del> how we talk of you here. You seem to have discovered the real secret, and that it is a big accomplishment.
I saw my medium the other day, and she told me an earful. The same thing all of them tell, of course; but with this addition: that I'll be called away from here in February - to New York! After she had talked quite awhile she suddenly said "The New York World". The^n she asked what that meant, adding that she supposed it meant that New York was really the world now, and I'd be called there. She said she heard my guide tell her this, and he said I'd been a fool in under-rating myself. The peculiar thing is that I don't in the least believe 

